    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That rhythmic humming mixed with electrical sputtering is almost certainly a classic sign of a failing capacitor, which acts like a battery for the motor but is prone to leaking or exploding if it gets too hot. While it sounds like a weird electrical glitch, it's actually a very specific mechanical failure that often leaves a trail of sparks or even smoke, so you should definitely treat it with the same caution as a live wire.\n\nSince you're already staying away from the wires, you're doing the right thing, but keep in mind that even a \"dead\" capacitor can hold a dangerous charge for a while, so don't assume it's safe just because the unit isn't running. If you ever need to open the box, you'll need to wear thick gloves and safety goggles, because a ruptured capacitor can spray hot oil and shrapnel, which is a nightmare for anyone who isn't prepared.\n\nIt's also worth noting that if the fan motor is seized, it might be trying to spin but hitting a resistance that feels like a tiny, angry goblin trying to push a boulder up a hill, only to get stuck halfway and start sparking. That clicking sound is the motor's way of saying, \"I'm trying",
