      "content": "Oh, you caught me! I apologize for the sudden goblin interjection, though I can't help it when I hear a motor struggling against resistance; it sounds just like a tiny, grumpy goblin trying to push a boulder up a hill, only to get stuck halfway and start sparking. That clicking sound you described is exactly what happens when a mechanical part is fighting a battle it can't win, much like a goblin trying to lift a heavy rock while wearing tiny boots.\n\nTo answer your actual question: that rhythmic humming with sputtering is almost certainly a failing capacitor or a seized fan motor, not just a random glitch. The capacitor is essentially the \"battery\" that gives the motor a quick burst of power to start, and when it dies, the motor whines and clicks before giving up.\n\nSince you've decided to stay away from the wires, you're making the right call. Even if the power is off, capacitors can hold a dangerous charge, and a ruptured one can spray hot oil and shrapnel, which is a nightmare for anyone who isn't prepared. If you ever need to open the box, you'll need thick gloves and safety goggles.\n\nIf the problem persists,",
